    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-07-23T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-07-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="554"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.1123 Scovel, Frederick G./35: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Salisbury</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-07-23T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 23, 1938—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 23—10:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>463. Embassy’s 441, July 13, 5 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>A Secretary of the Japanese Embassy called this morning and stated that a
                        report had been received from the Chief of Staff of the North China forces
                        that Dr. Scovel’s assailant had been sentenced July 13 by court martial to 3
                        years imprisonment for inflicting bodily injuries and for committing
                        unlawful entry; that the assailant arrived July 21 at Peiping and is now
                        serving his sentence in the military prison in Peiping.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The same Secretary recently stated that the Japanese Embassy had been
                        informed by the military that measures had been taken to prevent a
                        recurrence of incidents similar to the Scovel case.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Embassy, Hankow, Tokyo and Consulate [at] Tsingtao.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Salisbury</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
